INTERFACE VS ABSTRACT CLASS

This note is written for beginners.
Both interface and abstract class are used when we want to create a common rule
for multiple classes. But they are used in slightly different situations.

1) SIMPLE IDEA

Abstract class:
Use an abstract class when classes are closely related and should share both
common data and common behavior.

Interface:
Use an interface when you want to describe a common ability or action that many
different classes can have.

2) EASY REAL LIFE EXAMPLE

Abstract class example:
Animal can be an abstract class.
Why?
Because all animals may have common data like name or age, and common methods
like eat() or sleep().
But each animal may make a different sound, so sound() can be abstract.

Interface example:
Flyable can be an interface.
Why?
Because bird, airplane, and drone are very different things, but all can fly.
So Flyable only describes the ability.

3) MAIN DIFFERENCE

Abstract class is about:
"What something is"

Interface is about:
"What something can do"

4) BEGINNER-FRIENDLY COMPARISON

Abstract class:
- A class can extend only one abstract class.
- It can have normal methods with full body.
- It can have abstract methods without body.
- It can have instance variables (fields).
- It can have constructors.
- It is useful when child classes need shared code.

Interface:
- A class can implement multiple interfaces.
- It is mainly used to define a contract.
- It tells what methods must exist.
- It is useful when unrelated classes share the same ability.

5) WHEN SHOULD YOU USE ABSTRACT CLASS?

Use abstract class when:
- You want to write common code once and reuse it.
- You want common fields like name, id, price, salary, etc.
- You want a parent-child relationship.
- You want some methods to be same for all child classes.
- You want some methods to be compulsory but written differently by each child.

Example:
abstract class Payment

Child classes:
- CardPayment
- UpiPayment
- CashPayment

Reason:
All payments may have common details, but the payment process can differ.

6) WHEN SHOULD YOU USE INTERFACE?

Use interface when:
- You want to define a rule or ability.
- Different classes may need the same behavior.
- The classes are not necessarily from the same family.
- You want one class to follow multiple rules.

Example:
interface Printable

Classes that can implement it:
- Report
- Invoice
- PhotoDocument

Reason:
All these classes are different, but all can be printed.

7) VERY IMPORTANT MEMORY TRICK

Abstract class:
Common base + shared code

Interface:
Common ability + rule

8) SHORT EXAMPLE THINKING

If you say:
"All these objects are a type of Payment"
-> abstract class makes sense

If you say:
"All these objects can be printed"
-> interface makes sense

9) FINAL CONCLUSION

Use abstract class when you need:
- inheritance
- shared fields
- shared methods
- partial implementation

Use interface when you need:
- common behavior
- flexibility
- multiple abilities in the same class

10) ONE-LINE DIFFERENCE

Abstract class = shared parent with some ready-made code
Interface = rule book that tells a class what it must do
